    background: `Madhubani (also called Mithila) painting is a living visual tradition from the Mithila region of northern Bihar, India, practiced primarily by women for over 2,500 years. The art's origins are tied to the Ramayana — the Maithili text Valmiki Ramayana describes King Janaka commanding artists to decorate his kingdom for the wedding of his daughter Sita to Lord Ram, and Mithila (modern-day Darbhanga-Madhubani district in Bihar) is traditionally identified as Janaka's kingdom. For millennia, Madhubani painting was an exclusively domestic and ritual practice: women painted the interior walls of their homes (kohbar ghar — the bridal chamber), the exterior walls facing the village street (aripan floor designs), and ceremonial objects used in Hindu rites of passage from birth through death.

The visual vocabulary of Madhubani is highly codified. Specific deities, symbols, and motifs carry ritual meanings that have been transmitted mother-to-daughter for generations: the fish represents fertility and prosperity; the lotus symbolizes purity; the sun and moon represent eternal cycles; the bamboo grove indicates marriage and new beginnings. Human and divine figures are rendered in stylized profile with large expressive eyes. Every surface within the composition is filled — there are no empty spaces — in the Bharni (filling) style, while the Kachni (outline) style uses intricate single-line patterns. Natural pigments were traditionally extracted from plants (turmeric, indigo, leaves of various plants), minerals (ochre, lamp black), and cow-derived materials (cow dung for white, cowpat ash for gray).`,
    decline: `Madhubani painting's near-disappearance in the 20th century was precipitated by material and social changes that eroded both its medium and its ritual context. The widespread adoption of cement plaster walls replaced the traditional mud-plaster surfaces that accepted natural pigments and formed an integral part of the art's aesthetic. As plaster walls became standard in rural Bihar, the wall-painting tradition became technically difficult to maintain. Simultaneously, the commercialization of Hindu ritual life reduced the demand for elaborate home-based ritual paintings: factory-printed images of deities, mass-produced calendar art, and imported decorative materials displaced hand-painted walls as status markers.

Social changes also played a role. As Bihar's rural economy stagnated in the mid-20th century, male migration to cities for work restructured household economies. Women who might previously have dedicated weeks to elaborate ritual paintings faced increased household labor burdens without the social support structures that had historically made communal painting sessions possible. The severe Bihar famine of 1966–67 accelerated these pressures, and it was precisely this crisis that provided the unlikely catalyst for Madhubani's transformation.`,
    revivalStrategy: `The revival of Madhubani painting is one of the most successful craft revival stories in post-independence India. The critical turning point came in 1966–67 when Pupul Jayakar, a cultural advisor to Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, sent artist Bhaskar Kulkarni to Bihar's famine-affected Madhubani district with instructions to provide relief through artwork commissions. Kulkarni encouraged women to translate their wall paintings onto paper — creating portable, saleable artworks for the first time. The experiment was transformative: within months, Madhubani paintings were exhibited in Delhi and Bombay galleries to extraordinary acclaim, and a new market was born.

Today, Madhubani painting is one of India's most commercially successful folk arts. The Geographical Indication (GI) tag granted in 2007 protects authentic Madhubani work and commands premium pricing. Organizations like the Crafts Development Center in Madhubani, the Bihar Handloom and Handicrafts Corporation, and numerous NGOs provide materials, training, and market linkage for over 15,000 active practitioners in Madhubani district alone. The art has been adopted by international fashion brands (Fabindia, Anokhi) for textile prints, by UNICEF for greeting cards, and by the Indian Railways, which has decorated the interiors of multiple trains with Madhubani murals.`,
    tourismOpportunities: `Madhubani town and surrounding Mithila villages have become significant craft tourism destinations in Bihar. The Bihar Tourism Development Corporation offers "Mithila Art Trail" packages that bring visitors to artist homes and workshops in Jitwarpur, Ranti, and Andha villages — the three major centers for different Madhubani styles (Brahmin Bharni, Kayastha Kachni, and Harijan Gond-influenced work). The annual Mithila Mahotsav festival draws thousands of visitors each year with live painting demonstrations, exhibitions, and cultural programs.

The international market for Madhubani art has expanded dramatically, with Indian diaspora communities worldwide as a major customer base. Authentic large-format Madhubani paintings by recognized masters sell for ₹5,000–₹2,00,000 in India and significantly more in international galleries. Madhubani-based fashion collaborations with European luxury brands are creating premium revenue streams, while online platforms like Etsy and dedicated craft marketplaces have allowed individual artists to sell directly to global buyers, with some top practitioners earning ₹8–15 lakh annually.`,
